description:
## Severity
Major
## Dimension
security
## Location
src/tools/bash/kill.rs:35, 42, 57
## Violation
The process killer invokes `Command::new("kill")` three times — resolved via `$PATH`. Because `apply_env_scrub` does NOT scrub `PATH` (policy.rs:143-151 is denylist), a malicious or compromised `PATH` entry can shadow `kill` and either fail-open (let the runaway child survive) or escalate privileges. The code also `let _`-swallows the return of every shell-out.

Quoted (kill.rs:34-42):
```
        // Step 1: Send SIGTERM to the entire process group
        let _ = Command::new("kill").args(["-TERM", &neg_pid_str]).output();

        // Step 2: Wait up to 2 seconds for the process to exit
        let deadline = Instant::now() + Duration::from_secs(2);
        let mut exited = false;
        while Instant::now() < deadline {
            // `kill -0` checks if process exists without sending a signal
            let check = Command::new("kill").args(["-0", &pid_str]).output();
```
## Mandated refactor
1. Replace the `Command::new("kill")` shell-outs with `nix::sys::signal::killpg` / `nix::sys::signal::kill` (libc calls — no PATH lookup, no fork/exec).
2. Use `nix::sys::wait::waitpid` with `WNOHANG` instead of `kill -0` polling.
3. Propagate the result of the signal call instead of `let _`-discarding it; surface failures up to the caller so a wedged kill is observable.
